		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [3.60]</nobr><br><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Beleni&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p> Here are a couple thoughts I had about your questions. They may not be 100% accurate, because I don't take notes on this kind of stuff, I just go on how it has seemed for me...<br><br>1. There really isn't a way to know except to follow the formula. There is no box that pops up and tells you, but it is like Tymothy, the formula is basically your level multiplied by five, then add five to that and that is your skill cap for that level. For instance, you are at level 7. Multiply level seven by 5 to get 35. Add 5 to that and you have 40. That is your skill cap for that level. This isn't for skills such as tailoring or blacksmithing, however, as I've heard there is no limit on those determined by your level. This is for skills such as sense heading, mend, 1-2 handed bashing, etc...<br><br>2. Max out your skills by hitting the buttons over and over and over again for skills that require button-hitting. Sense heading, mend, etc. Though I tended to time my mend skill with fights, so I wouldn't hit it right before a fight then not have it available when I needed it (even if it did poop out on me and not work ;) But if you're running around, hit that mend buttong. Sitting on the boat and it comes up? Hit it. Same with all your skills. <br> Now, with a skill such as one handed bash and whatnot...I've heard that you have to fight mobs that at least give you experience in order to raise these skills. I don't know if this is true or not, but it might be a good idea to stick with blue mobs at least. The idea here is to use a weapon (if you're practicing a skill that involves a weapon, compared to something like punch) with a very low delay. That way, you hit the mob more often and have more opportunities to raise your skill. If you're using a weapon that hits hard but has a very high delay, you're not going to hit the mob as much so your skill won't go up as quickly. <br> At level 7, you're still at the stage where levelling occurs rather quickly, that's probably why you're not maxing out your skills. When you get a little higher and it takes longer to level, it will seem to go much faster. Also, as you get better at something, it takes less time to raise the skill. For instance, when I hit about level 15 or so, it only took a few minutes to max out sense heading. Other skills, such as feign death and instill doubt are much much harder to raise, and you should probably look at some of the older messages here that have covered those awhile back. <br> And as for your mend skill, just give it time and you'll see it jump dramatically. Again, by the time I was at least level 15 (I don't know if it was exactly this level, but around then) I could reasonably rely on it to work most of the time. I don't know that your mend is really working less often that others, I think it probably just seems that way.<br> Anyway, good luck, and I hope you stick with it. A monk is an awesome character to play and when you get your skills up there you'll find them very handy to have. Maybe someone else can post some more pointers and maybe stuff I've missed. <br>Happy Hunting,<br>Beleni.</p><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Beleni<br>Lowly Monk on Karana</td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >0 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td class=mhback align=right><span class=mh id=fs8><a class=mh href=/db/classes.html?class=3><img src=/shared/root_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Up" width=17 height=11> Thread Index</a> |  <a clas